revision.text:
{{Infobox earthquake |title= 1932 Changma earthquake |timestamp = 1932-12-25 02:04:30 |isc-event = 906530 |anss-url = iscgem906530 |local-date = {{Start date|1932|12|25}} |local-time = 10:04:30 |map2 = {{Location map | Tibetan Plateau | label= | lat=39.7 | long=96.7 | mark=Bullseye1.png | marksize=40 | position=top | width= 250 | float=right | caption=}} |magnitude = 7.6 {{M|s|link=y}} |depth= |location={{coord|39.7|96.7|display=inline,title}}<ref name="NGDC">{{cite web|url=http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/nndc/struts/results?eq_0=3507&t=101650&s=13&d=22,26,13,12&nd=display|title=Comments for the Significant Earthquake|author=NGDC|accessdate=2 November 2010}}</ref> |countries affected = [[Republic of China (1912–1949)|Republic of China]] |intensity = [[Mercalli intensity scale|X (''Extreme'')]]<ref name="NGDC"/> |casualties = 275 }} The '''1932 Changma earthquake''' occurred at 10:04:27 local time (02:04:07 [[Coordinated universal time|UTC]]) on 25 December. With an estimated magnitude of 7.6 on the [[surface wave magnitude]] scale, and a maximum felt intensity of X (''Extreme'') on the [[Mercalli intensity scale]], the quake destroyed 1,167 houses, and 275 people were killed with a further 320 injured.<ref name="NGDC"/>
==Tectonic setting== The [[earthquake]] was located close to the northern margin of the [[Tibetan Plateau]]. This area of thickened crust is a result of the ongoing collision of the [[Indo-Australian Plate]] with the [[Eurasian Plate]]. The way in which this zone accommodates the collision remains unclear with two end-member models being proposed. The first regards the crust as being made up of a mosaic of strong blocks separated by weak [[Fault (geology)|fault zones]], the microplate model. The second regards the deformation as being continuous within the mid to lower crust, the continuum model. The change in width of the deformed zone along the collisional belt, with the narrow zone of western Tibet compared to the main part of the Tibetan Plateau, is explained as either lateral escape to the east along the [[Altyn Tagh fault|Altyn Tagh]] and [[Karakorum fault]]s in the microplate model or as the effect of the rigid Tarim Basin block causing heterogeneous deformation within a generally weaker lithosphere in the continuum model.<ref name="Cowgill">{{cite journal|last=Cowgill |first=E. |author2=Yin, A. |author3=Harrison T.M. |author4=Xiao-Feng, W. |year=2003 |title=Reconstruction of the Altyn Tagh fault based on U-Pb geochronology: Role of back thrusts, mantle sutures, and heterogeneous crustal strength in forming the Tibetan Plateau |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research |volume=108 |issue=B7 |page=2346 |doi=10.1029/2002JB002080 |url=http://sims.ess.ucla.edu/PDF/Cowgill_et_al_2003_Jour%20Geophys%20Res.pdf |accessdate=3 November 2010 |bibcode=2003JGRB..108.2346C |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718114705/http://sims.ess.ucla.edu/PDF/Cowgill_et_al_2003_Jour%20Geophys%20Res.pdf |archivedate=18 July 2010 |df= |citeseerx=10.1.1.458.2239 }}</ref> At its northern end, the Altyn Tagh fault progressively loses displacement by its interaction with a series of WNW–ESE trending structures, mostly with components of reverse displacement and sinistral (left lateral) strike-slip. The Changma fault is one of those structures.<ref name="Meyer">{{cite journal |doi=10.1046/j.1365-246X.1998.00567.x |last=Meyer |first=B. |author2=Tapponnier, P. |author3=Bourjot, L. |author4=Métivier, F. |author5=Gaudemer, Y. |author6=Peltzer, G. |author7=Shunmin, G. |author8=Zhitai, C.|year=1998 |title=Crustal thickening in Gansu-Qinghai, lithospheric mantle subduction, and oblique, strike-slip controlled growth of the Tibetan plateau |journal=[[Geophysical Journal International]] |volume=135 |issue=1 |pages=1–47 |bibcode=1998GeoJI.135....1M}}</ref>
==Damage== The region stricken by this earthquake included the entire [[Changma Basin]] and the western part of the [[Hexi Corridor]] in [[Gansu province]].<ref name="NGDC"/> The greatest damage occurred in Changma. In [[Gaotai County|Gaotai]], [[Jinta County|Jinta]], [[Guazhou County|Anxi]] and [[Dingxing County|Dingxin]] part of the city walls and some buildings collapsed and many houses were damaged. In the town of Changma all 800 families were affected, 270 people died and at least another 300 were injured; deaths were also recorded in Gaotai (3) and Jinta (2).<ref name="NGDC"/>
==Characteristics== A [[surface rupture]] of about 116&nbsp;km was identified after the earthquake, including five separate fault segments,<ref name="NGDC"/> the largest rupture observed for a reverse-slip event in Asia in the twentieth century.<ref name="Chen">{{cite journal |last=Chen |first=Y.-G. |author2=Chen, W.-S. |author3=Wang, Y. |author4=Lo, P.W. |author5=Liu, T.K. |author6=Lee, J.C. |year=2002 |title=Geomorphic evidence for prior earthquakes: Lessons from the 1999 Chichi earthquake in central Taiwan |journal=Geology |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages=171–174 |doi=10.1130/0091-7613(2002)030<0171:GEFPEL>2.0.CO;2 |url=http://ashan.gl.ntu.edu.tw/publication/Publication-info_20100423/43.%20Geomorphic%20evidence%20for%20prior%20earthquakes%20Lessons%20from%20the%201999%20Chichi%20earthquake%20in%20central%20Taiwan.pdf |accessdate=18 November 2010|bibcode = 2002Geo....30..171C }}</ref> Four of the segments that ruptured were reverse faults, the fifth was a strike-slip fault. Vertical offsets of more than a metre were observed on most of the segments, with a maximum of 5 m.<ref name="Rubin">{{cite journal |last=Rubin |first=C.M. |year=1996 |title=Systematic underestimation of earthquake magnitudes from large intracontinental reverse faults: Historical ruptures break across segment boundaries |pages=989 |journal=Geology |volume=24 |issue=11 |doi=10.1130/0091-7613(1996)024<0989:SUOEMF>2.3.CO;2 |url=http://geology.geoscienceworld.org/cgi/content/abstract/24/11/989 |accessdate=18 November 2010|bibcode = 1996Geo....24..989R |hdl=2060/19980029715 }}</ref>
==Seismic hazard implications == The 1932 Changma earthquake shows that apparently separate mapped intracontinental reverse faults may rupture simultaneously in an earthquake. Estimates of the [[seismic hazard]] in an area based on the rupture of single reverse faults may lead to a major underestimate of the magnitudes of the largest possible earthquake.<ref name="Rubin"/>
