'''''Al-Houriya''''' ({{lang-ar|الحرية}}, meaning ''Freedom'') is a weekly [[Arabic language]] newspaper in [[Mauritania]]. The director of the newspaper is Mohamed Nema Oumar.<ref name="allafrica 200807230024">{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200807230024.html|title=Mauritania: Journalist, Publisher Arrested Over Article On Judicial Corruption|date=2008-07-23|work=Reporters sans Frontières (Paris)|access-date=2018-07-18}}</ref>
==Arrests== On 12 June 2008, Mohamed Nema Oumar, managing editor of ''Al-Houriya'', was arrested by the Mauritanian police after he published an article on Senator El Had and his activities in Israel.<ref name="africagm 2008/7/27">[http://africa.gm/africa/mauritania/nouakchott/article/2008/7/27/mauritania-alert-second-al-houriya-newspaper-journalist-detained-in-a-month Mauritania ALERT: Second Al Houriya newspaper journalist detained in a month], ''Africa.gm'', 27 July 2008</ref> Oumar was arrested at the airport on his way back from Libya where he accompanied the Mauritanian President with an accredited press badge.<ref>[http://afrol.com/articles/29421 Mauritania President "tried to stop journalist's detention"], ''Afrol.com'', 17 June 2008</ref> Mohamed Nema Oumar was detained for 30 hours, and charged two days later with libel and insults. His passport was retained for 2 months.<ref name="allafrica 200807230024"/><ref>[https://rsf.org/en/news/libel-charge-brought-against-publisher-arabic-language-weekly Libel charge brought against publisher of Arabic-language weekly], ''Rsf.org], 16 June 2008</ref> He is jailed again starting 21 July.<ref name="ifj 117">[http://www.ifj.org/nc/news-single-view/browse/117/backpid/32/category/africa-2/article/ifj-calls-for-release-of-journalist-and-publisher-held-over-corrupted-judges-story-in-mauritania/ IFJ Calls for Release of Journalist and Publisher Held Over Corrupted Judges Story in Mauritania], ''Ifj.org'', 6 August 2008</ref>
In July 2008, Mohammed Ould Abdel Latif, editor of ''Al-Houriya'', was also arrested and detained by the Mauritanian police the day he published an article about corruption and briberies collected by high court judges.<ref name="africagm 2008/7/27"/> His article stipulated that these judges had received 68,650 euros to release a businessman and a policeman accused of drug trafficking.<ref>[https://www.somalinet.com/library/news-archive/english/Africa/16265 Mauritania: Two journalists arrested in drugs libel case], ''Somalinet.com'', 23 July 2008</ref>
On 6 August 2008, the [[International Federation of Journalists]] (IFJ) called for the release of the two journalists.<ref name="ifj 117"/>
