{{Second Messenian War}}

The '''Battle of the Great Foss''' occurred in 682 BC during the [[Second Messenian War]] (685–668 BC). The word "foss" derives from the Latin [[wiktionary:fossa#Latin|fossa]], meaning "ditch" or "trench."<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SsEtm9CNCc0C&lpg=PP156&ots=Z3DAanOdU4&dq=foss%20trench%20ancient%20greek&pg=PP156#v=onepage&q&f=true|title=The Complete Dictionary of Arts and Sciences. In which the Whole Circle of Human Learning is Explained, and the Difficulties Attending the Acquisition of Every Art, Whether Liberal Or Mechanical, are Removed, in the Most Easy and Familiar Manner ...|last=Croker|first=Temple Henry|last2=Clark|first2=Samuel|last3=(Londres)|first3=John Coote|last4=Williams|first4=Thomas|last5=(Londres)|first5=James Fletcher|last6=(Dublin)|first6=William Smith|date=1765|publisher=authors, and sold|language=en}}</ref> According to ancient historian ''Pausanias'' the outcome of the battle was determined by trickery. The Spartans bribed Aristocrates, the king of the [[Arcadia (ancient region)#Arcadians|Arcadians]], to withdraw his men just as the battle was beginning. This resulted in the slaughter of the Messenians.<ref>Montagu, ''Battles of the Greek and Roman Worlds'', 49.</ref>

